In this assignment we are going to explore the concept of sampling distributions and analysis of various types of data. Please type your commands below in the space provided.

Problem 1. (24 points)

First download the dataset MEASURESOFBIRTHANDDEATH.csv provided on the Canvas site and upload the file to RStudio (on the lower right window Files -> Upload, then follow the instructions).

a. Read the file in RStudio by using read.csv() command.
Solution

Type your code below.

data = read.csv("MEASURESOFBIRTHANDDEATH.csv")

One of the columns in the dataset is called LBW, which gives proportion of low birth weights (<2500 gr) for counties. In the problems that follow please non-standard values are NOT coded as NA. Make certain you remove them before doing the sampling.

b. Select a random sample of size 20 from LBW without replacement.
Solution

Type your code below.

good = data[data$LBW>0,]

The central limit theorem states that if you take a large enough sample from any population, the sample mean will have an approximately Normal distribution with the mean being the same as the population and the standard deviation equal to the standard deviation of the population divided by the square root of the sample size. The standard deviation of the sample mean is known as the standard error of the sample mean.

Problem 2. (4 points)

Range in statistics is a measure of variation and defined as follows: Range = Maximimum Value - Minimum Value. Write a new function called MyRange to calculate this measure for a numerical input vector and test it on LBW variable in the MEASURESOFBIRTHANDDEATH.csv file.

Solution

Type your code below.

MyRange = function(x){
  range = max(x) - min(x)
  return(range)
}
MyRange(good$LBW)
## [1] 13.5
Problem 3. (4 points)

Write a function that takes two search strings (by using twitteR) as arguments and that returns the results of a Poisson rate ratio test on the arrival rates of tweets on the two topics. Your function should first run the necessary Twitter searches, then sort the tweets by ascending time of arrival and calculate the two vectors of time differentials. Use the mean of one of these vectors as the basis for comparison and for each vector, count how many events are at or below the mean. Use this information and the numbers of tweets requested to run the poisson.test() rate comparison.

Solution

Type your code below.

library(twitteR)
library(rtweet)
## 
## Attaching package: 'rtweet'
## The following object is masked from 'package:twitteR':
## 
##     lookup_statuses
auth_as("Twitter Authentication 2023")
## Reading auth from '/home/wanne051/.config/R/rtweet/Twitter Authentication
## 2023.rds'
TweetFrame=function(tag,n=100,fn=paste0(tag,".rdata")){
  require(rtweet)
  require(fs)
  fn=path_sanitize(fn)
  auth_as("Twitter Authentication 2023")
  
  if(file.exists(fn)){
    load(fn)
  } else {
    tweetList <- search_tweets(tag, n=n)
    save(tweetList, file=fn)
  }
  return(tweetList)
  
}

PoissonRateRatioTest = function(searchString1, searchString2){
  tweetDF1 = TweetFrame(searchString1, n = 500)
  tweetDF2 = TweetFrame(searchString2, n = 500)
  
  sortweetsDF1 = tweetDF1[order(as.integer(tweetDF1$created)), ]
  sortweetsDF2 = tweetDF2[order(as.integer(tweetDF2$created)), ]
  
  eventDelays1 = as.integer(diff(sortweetsDF1$created))
  eventDelays2 = as.integer(diff(sortweetsDF2$created))
  
  mu = mean(eventDelays1)
  s1 = sum(eventDelays1<=mu)
  s2 = sum(eventDelays2<=mu)
  
  return(poisson.test(c(s1, s2), c(500, 500)))

}

PoissonRateRatioTest("#ladygaga", "#oprah")
